Alice will lose.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [0,1]\nOutput: true\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3]\nOutput: true\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 1000\n0 <= nums[i] < 216\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def xorGame(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def xorGame(self, nums: List[int]) -> bool:\n        # Calculate the initial XOR of all elements\n        total_xor = 0\n        for num in nums:\n            total_xor ^= num\n        \n        # If the initial XOR is 0, Alice wins immediately\n        if total_xor == 0:\n            return True\n        \n        # If the number of elements is even, Alice wins\n        # because she can always force Bob into a losing position\n        return len(nums) % 2 == 0\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- The key observation is the property of XOR: if the XOR of all elements is 0 at the start, Alice wins immediately because she starts her turn with a winning condition.\n- If the XOR of all elements is not 0, the game depends on the number of elements:\n  - If the number of elements is even, Alice can always mirror Bob's moves, ensuring that she never faces a losing position.\n  - If the number of elements is odd, Bob can always mirror Alice's moves, ensuring that Alice faces the losing position eventually.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}